			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2015</a> paper:</span><br><i>Using decision rules for solving conflicts in extended feature models</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/LinaOchoa.html">Lina Ochoa</a>, <a href="../profile/OscarGonzálezRojas.html">Oscar González-Rojas</a>, <a href="../profile/ThomasThüm.html">Thomas Thüm</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2814251.2814263">10.1145/2814251.2814263</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2c.html"><span class="tagM">T2C: Variability</span></a><ul><li> The paper addresses variability management and conflict resolution in feature models for product lines.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a><ul><li> It uses model-based transformation/processing to analyze or resolve feature-model conflicts.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> Conflict detection/resolution is formulated as analysis over the feature-model language description.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a><ul><li> The work typically includes evaluation on feature models/scenarios to demonstrate effectiveness (as implied by decision-making scenarios).
</li></ul></li></ul>
